The object with id bb is the second sub object within the second "subs" array, which has id "x", and "P":"j", "O":"i". It's a nested object with id "bb", "J":"d", "subs":[...]. It contains two children, with id "cb" and "I":"c", and id "db" and "H":"b".

If you want an excerpt from the JSON file, it's quite complex because you'll need to get both levels of the JSON object (the root object and the sub object) before extracting information from the latter. It involves some path navigation.

Assuming you want an excerpt from the "subs" array of the root object, you can use a JSONPath expression like this:


```json
{
  "$..subs[?(@.id == 'x')][0].subs[?(@.id == 'bb')][0].subs[?(@.id == 'cb')][0].subs[?(@.id == 'db')][0].id"
}
```
This expression selects the first sub-sub-object of the first level of the "subs" array with id "x", then selects the first sub-object of that sub-sub-object with id "bb", then selects the first sub-sub-object of that sub-object with id "cb", and finally selects the "id" field of that sub-sub-object.

In JSONPath, `$` is used to navigate up from a node to its parent, `.` is used to access an attribute or a property of an object or a node, and `[]` is used to apply a filter to a node or a path.

The result will be the "id" field of the object with id "db".

Note: If you're not familiar with JSONPath, it's worth learning as it's a powerful tool for navigating and selecting data from JSON documents. There are online tools that allow you to test JSONPath expressions.
